<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-using-logarithms-to-compute-products-and-ratios" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Using Logarithms to Compute Products and Ratios</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.2 Indices and Logarithms
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Apply common logarithms in multiplication, division, powers and roots of numbers
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that logarithms convert multiplication to addition, division to subtraction, and powers/roots to multiplication/division of logarithms.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Use logarithm tables to perform multiplication, division, and find powers and roots of numbers.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply logarithmic calculations to solve real-world problems involving areas, volumes, and compound calculations.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/indices-and-logarithms/using-logarithms-to-compute-products-and-ratios.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/indices-and-logarithms/step-by-step-guide_using-logarithms-to-compute-products-and-ratios.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery / Engage &amp; Explore</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Objective:</alert> To explore how logarithms simplify complex calculations.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Anchor Learning Experience: The Calculator Challenge</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            Students work in groups. In Part A, they try to compute <m>236.5 \times 42.8</m>, <m>528.6 \div 24.7</m>, and <m>\sqrt[3]{524.8}</m> without using a calculator. In Part B, they use logarithm tables to find <m>\log(236.5)</m> and <m>\log(42.8)</m>, and discover what happens when they add these two logarithms and find the antilog of the sum.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Discussion Questions:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li><p>How does adding logarithms relate to multiplication?</p></li>
                <li><p>How does subtracting logarithms relate to division?</p></li>
                <li><p>What operation on logarithms gives you a power?</p></li>
                <li><p>What operation on logarithms gives you a root?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> Circulate among groups, asking probing questions. Guide students to discover that <m>\log(a \times b) = \log(a) + \log(b)</m> and <m>\log(a \div b) = \log(a) - \log(b)</m>. Use student discoveries to bridge to formal instruction.
        </p>
    </axiom>




    <activity xml:id="act-calculator-challenge">
        <title>The Calculator Challenge</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Work in groups to explore the following challenge.</p>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Part A: The Long Way</title>
                <p>Without using a calculator, try to compute:</p>
                <ol>
                    <li><p><m>236.5 \times 42.8</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>528.6 \div 24.7</m></p></li>
                    <!-- <li><p><m>\sqrt[3]{524.8}</m></p></li> -->
                </ol>
            </paragraphs>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Part B: Discovering the Pattern</title>
                <p>Use your logarithm tables to find:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><p><m>\log(236.5)</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\log(42.8)</m></p></li>
                    <li><p>What do you notice when you add these two logarithms?</p></li>
                    <li><p>What happens when you find the antilog of the sum?</p></li>
                </ul>
            </paragraphs>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Discussion Questions</title>
                <ol>
                    <li><p>How does adding logarithms relate to multiplication?</p></li>
                    <li><p>How does subtracting logarithms relate to division?</p></li>
                    <li><p>What operation on logarithms gives you a power?</p></li>
                    <li><p>What operation on logarithms gives you a root?</p></li>
                </ol>
            </paragraphs>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <insight xml:id="ins-multiplicative-log-laws">
        <title>Multiplicative Laws of Logarithms</title>
        <statement>
            <p>The main laws used for calculations are:</p>
            <ol>
                <li><p><m>\log(ab)=\log a+\log b</m> — Product Law (multiply by adding logs)</p></li>
                <li><p><m>\log(a/b)=\log a-\log b</m> — Quotient Law (divide by subtracting logs)</p></li>
                <!-- <li><p><m>\log(a^n)=n\log a</m> — Power Law (powers become multipliers)</p></li> -->
                <!-- <li><p><m>\log(\sqrt[n]{a})=\tfrac{1}{n}\log a</m> — Root Law (roots divide the log)</p></li> -->
            </ol>
            <p>The general process: find the logs, apply the operation (+, −, ×, ÷ on logs), then find the antilog of the result.</p>
            <p><em>Misconception:</em> <strong>log(a+b) ≠ log a + log b</strong>. The laws only apply to multiplication, division, powers and roots.</p>
        </statement>
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction / Explain</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Objective:</alert> To formalize the laws of logarithms for multiplication, division, powers, and roots.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Key Takeaways — The Four Laws of Logarithms for Calculations:</alert>
        </p>
        <p>
            1. <alert>Product Law (Multiplication):</alert> <m>\log(a \times b) = \log(a) + \log(b)</m>. To multiply: ADD the logarithms, then find antilog.
        </p>
        <p>
            2. <alert>Quotient Law (Division):</alert> <m>\log(a \div b) = \log(a) - \log(b)</m>. To divide: SUBTRACT the logarithms, then find antilog.
        </p>
        <p>
            3. <alert>Power Law:</alert> <m>\log(a^b) = b \times \log(a)</m>. To find a power: MULTIPLY the logarithm by the exponent, then find antilog.
        </p>
        <p>
            4. <alert>Root Law:</alert> <m>\log(\sqrt[n]{a}) = \frac{1}{n} \times \log(a)</m>. To find a root: DIVIDE the logarithm by the root index, then find antilog.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>The General Process:</alert> Step 1: Find <m>\log</m> of each number from tables. Step 2: Apply the appropriate operation (+, −, ×, ÷). Step 3: Find antilog of the result.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Addressing Misconceptions:</alert> <q>Remember: <m>\log(a + b) \neq \log(a) + \log(b)</m>. The laws only work for multiplication, division, powers, and roots — NOT for addition or subtraction!</q>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="ex-multiplication-using-logs">
        <title>Multiplication using Logarithms</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Find <m>236.5 \times 42.8</m> using logarithm tables.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Step 1: From tables, <m>\log(236.5)=2.3741</m> and <m>\log(42.8)=1.6318</m>.</p>
            <p>Step 2: Add the logs: <m>2.3741+1.6318=4.0059</m>.</p>
            <p>Step 3: Antilog of <m>4.0059</m> gives <m>\approx 10\,160</m>, so <m>236.5\times42.8\approx10\,160</m>.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-division-using-logs">
        <title>Division using Logarithms</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Find <m>528.6 \div 24.7</m> using logarithm tables.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Step 1: From tables, <m>\log(528.6)=2.7233</m> and <m>\log(24.7)=1.3927</m>.</p>
            <p>Step 2: Subtract the logs: <m>2.7233-1.3927=1.3306</m>.</p>
            <p>Step 3: Antilog of <m>1.3306</m> gives <m>\approx 21.4</m>, so <m>528.6\div24.7\approx21.4</m>.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Objective:</alert> To apply logarithm laws to perform calculations.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Learning Experience:</alert> Students work through worked examples for multiplication (<m>236.5 \times 42.8</m>), division (<m>528.6 \div 24.7</m>), and cube root (<m>\sqrt[3]{524.8}</m>) using logarithm tables. They follow the general process: find the logs, apply the operation, then find the antilog.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> Monitor students, emphasizing the correct sequence of steps and verifying answers.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-using-logs">
        <exercise xml:id="auto_t4kqc74o">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_3v7ni0mg">
                    Use logarithm tables to evaluate the following:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_a6tdqsfh">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_x58didbq" marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_y2sy99d4">
                            <p xml:id="auto_gbb9csze">
                                <m>345.6 \times 78.9</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_yenfxnat">
                            <p xml:id="auto_d6xg9026">
                                <m>6284 \times 92.5</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_nifyj5jv">
                            <p xml:id="auto_irjc0s7o">
                                <m>0.0482 \times 53.7</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        <answer>
            <p xml:id="auto_e7trpb5a">
                <ol xml:id="auto_hiodpgu3" marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_ruwq0p3r"><m> \approx 27\,267.84</m></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_olzi8vf2"><m> \approx 581\,270</m></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_mnb52z9g"><m> \approx 2.5883</m></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_2zfy0egn">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_6jfw8t4r">
                    Use logarithms to calculate:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_mbqullpl">
                    <ol xml:id="auto_j2o3ml8l" marker="(a)">
                        <li xml:id="auto_im3qggol">
                            <p xml:id="auto_fgijj88q">
                                <m>652.3 \div 12.7</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_5fg9vfik">
                            <p xml:id="auto_76oqodbf">
                                <m>0.0854 \div 3.42</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_xcgsglq3">
                            <p xml:id="auto_yj9g1ep3">
                                <m>4312 \div 58.3</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        <answer>
            <p xml:id="auto_bztcw7ga">
                <ol xml:id="auto_d5t0g9gu" marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_1ldz2gay"><m> \approx 51.3622</m></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_wh8adsxq"><m> \approx 0.024971</m></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_amcu11q0"><m> \approx 73.9623</m></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment / Evaluate (Exit Ticket)</title>
        <p>
            <alert>Objective:</alert> To formatively assess individual student understanding.
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Learning Experience:</alert> Students complete exit ticket questions individually:
            <ol>
                <li><p>Use logarithm tables to evaluate multiplications (e.g., <m>345.6 \times 78.9</m>)</p></li>
                <li><p>Use logarithms to calculate divisions (e.g., <m>652.3 \div 12.7</m>)</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge student understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
        </p>
    </axiom>
